  "prompt": "Is spot counselling for reserved candidates?",
  "response": "Spot counselling is a process often used in the context of college or university admissions to fill vacant seats after the regular rounds of counselling are complete. These vacancies can arise for various reasons, such as candidates withdrawing or not accepting the seats. \n\nSpot counselling is generally open to all candidates who meet the eligibility criteria, which may include both reserved and unreserved category candidates. However, the specifics can vary by institution or governing body. Sometimes, institutions might prioritize filling seats reserved for certain categories, such as SC, ST, OBC, or EWS, if these categories have unfilled spots. \n\nIf you belong to a reserved category and are concerned about whether spot counselling will be available for you, it's best to check the official notifications from the specific institution or examination authority you're dealing with. They will provide detailed information on eligibility, available seats, and any category-specific considerations.",
